      <!-- Adrian Frutiger -->
      <article class="bg-bg-elevated border border-text-primary/10 rounded-sm overflow-hidden">
        <div class="bg-accent-primary/10 border-b border-accent-primary/20 p-8">
          <h2 class="text-h1 font-bold text-text-primary mb-2">Adrian Frutiger</h2>
          <span class="text-body text-text-secondary block mb-1">1928–2015</span>
          <span
            class="inline-block bg-accent-primary text-white px-4 py-1 rounded-sm text-small font-medium"
            >Type Designer</span
          >
        </div>

        <div class="p-8">
          <h3 class="text-h2 font-semibold text-text-primary mb-6">
            The Father of Humanist Typography
          </h3>

          <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary mb-6">
            Swiss type designer Adrian Frutiger created some of the 20th century's most influential
            and readable typefaces. Unlike the cold neutrality of Helvetica, Frutiger's work
            combined modernist clarity with subtle humanist warmth—slightly varied stroke widths,
            open apertures, and calligraphic influences that make his typefaces supremely legible.
          </p>

          <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary mb-8">
            His philosophy centered on a simple question: does this typeface serve the reader? This
            human-centered approach made his work ideal for wayfinding, where legibility at distance
            and speed is paramount.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-h3 font-semibold text-text-primary mb-4">Notable Works</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 pl-6 mb-8">
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Univers (1957)</strong> — Systematic typeface family
              with humanist characteristics
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Frutiger (1976)</strong> — The quintessential
              humanist sans-serif for wayfinding
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Avenir (1988)</strong> — Geometric structure with
              humanist warmth
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Frutiger Next (1999)</strong> — Refined and expanded
              version for digital use
            </li>
          </ul>

          <blockquote
            class="border-l-4 border-accent-primary bg-bg-secondary pl-8 pr-6 py-6 my-8 italic"
          >
            <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-primary">
              "The text should be read without any effort. Often, readers do not notice that the
              success of the reading process is also dependent on the quality of the typeface."
            </p>
          </blockquote>

          <h4 class="text-h3 font-semibold text-text-primary mb-4">Impact on Humanist Modernism</h4>
          <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
            Frutiger proved that typefaces could be both contemporary and warm, systematic and
            human. His work laid the foundation for all humanist typography that followed,
            demonstrating that legibility and aesthetic beauty enhance rather than contradict each
            other.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Edward Tufte -->
      <article class="bg-bg-elevated border border-text-primary/10 rounded-sm overflow-hidden">
        <div class="bg-accent-primary/10 border-b border-accent-primary/20 p-8">
          <h2 class="text-h1 font-bold text-text-primary mb-2">Edward Tufte</h2>
          <span class="text-body text-text-secondary block mb-1">Born 1942</span>
          <span
            class="inline-block bg-accent-primary text-white px-4 py-1 rounded-sm text-small font-medium"
            >Information Designer & Author</span
          >
        </div>

        <div class="p-8">
          <h3 class="text-h2 font-semibold text-text-primary mb-6">
            The Master of Information Design
          </h3>

          <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary mb-6">
            Yale professor Edward Tufte revolutionized how we think about presenting complex
            information. His books—themselves masterworks of typography and layout—demonstrate that
            dense, sophisticated data can be supremely readable when designed with human cognitive
            needs in mind.
          </p>

          <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary mb-8">
            Tufte coined principles like maximizing the "data-ink ratio" and eliminating
            "chartjunk," advocating for designs that respect the reader's intelligence while making
            information effortlessly comprehensible.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-h3 font-semibold text-text-primary mb-4">Notable Works</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 pl-6 mb-8">
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary"
                >The Visual Display of Quantitative Information (1983)</strong
              >
              — Foundational text on data visualization
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Envisioning Information (1990)</strong> — Strategies
              for presenting complex data
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Visual Explanations (1997)</strong> — Images and
              quantities, evidence and narrative
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Beautiful Evidence (2006)</strong> — The practice of
              analytical design
            </li>
          </ul>

          <blockquote
            class="border-l-4 border-accent-primary bg-bg-secondary pl-8 pr-6 py-6 my-8 italic"
          >
            <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-primary">
              "Clutter and confusion are not attributes of information, they are failures of
              design."
            </p>
          </blockquote>

          <h4 class="text-h3 font-semibold text-text-primary mb-4">Impact on Humanist Modernism</h4>
          <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
            Tufte showed that respecting the reader means presenting information clearly,
            completely, and beautifully. His work proves that humanist principles—generous spacing,
            clear hierarchy, thoughtful typography—enable rather than hinder the communication of
            complex ideas.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Erik Spiekermann -->
      <article class="bg-bg-elevated border border-text-primary/10 rounded-sm overflow-hidden">
        <div class="bg-accent-primary/10 border-b border-accent-primary/20 p-8">
          <h2 class="text-h1 font-bold text-text-primary mb-2">Erik Spiekermann</h2>
          <span class="text-body text-text-secondary block mb-1">Born 1947</span>
          <span
            class="inline-block bg-accent-primary text-white px-4 py-1 rounded-sm text-small font-medium"
            >Type Designer & Graphic Designer</span
          >
        </div>

        <div class="p-8">
          <h3 class="text-h2 font-semibold text-text-primary mb-6">
            Champion of Readable, Warm Typography
          </h3>

          <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary mb-6">
            German designer Erik Spiekermann brought warmth and approachability to corporate and
            editorial typography. His typefaces combine technical precision with humanist charm,
            proving that professional design can feel friendly without sacrificing sophistication.
          </p>

          <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary mb-8">
            Spiekermann is also a passionate advocate for good typography in public spaces,
            believing that readable, well-designed communication is a civic responsibility.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-h3 font-semibold text-text-primary mb-4">Notable Works</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 pl-6 mb-8">
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">FF Meta (1991)</strong> — "The Helvetica of the
              1990s" with humanist warmth
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">ITC Officina (1990)</strong> — Typewriter-inspired
              sans and serif families
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">FF Unit (2003)</strong> — Utilitarian yet warm
              corporate typeface
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Deutsche Bahn Corporate Design</strong> —
              Comprehensive design system for German Railways
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Stop Stealing Sheep (1993)</strong> — Influential
              book on typography
            </li>
          </ul>

          <blockquote
            class="border-l-4 border-accent-primary bg-bg-secondary pl-8 pr-6 py-6 my-8 italic"
          >
            <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-primary">
              "We don't believe in type. We believe in typography."
            </p>
          </blockquote>

          <h4 class="text-h3 font-semibold text-text-primary mb-4">Impact on Humanist Modernism</h4>
          <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
            Spiekermann demonstrated that corporate and institutional design can embrace humanist
            principles. His work proved that warmth and professionalism aren't contradictory—they're
            complementary. Organizations worldwide adopted his typefaces, bringing humanist
            modernism to millions of readers.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Matthew Carter -->
      <article class="bg-bg-elevated border border-text-primary/10 rounded-sm overflow-hidden">
        <div class="bg-accent-primary/10 border-b border-accent-primary/20 p-8">
          <h2 class="text-h1 font-bold text-text-primary mb-2">Matthew Carter</h2>
          <span class="text-body text-text-secondary block mb-1">Born 1937</span>
          <span
            class="inline-block bg-accent-primary text-white px-4 py-1 rounded-sm text-small font-medium"
            >Type Designer</span
          >
        </div>

        <div class="p-8">
          <h3 class="text-h2 font-semibold text-text-primary mb-6">
            Master of Screen-Optimized Typography
          </h3>

          <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary mb-6">
            British-American type designer Matthew Carter created typefaces that prioritize function
            and readability under real-world constraints. From phone directories to early computer
            screens, Carter's work exemplifies humanist modernism's core principle: design must
            serve actual human needs in actual conditions.
          </p>

          <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary mb-8">
            His Verdana and Georgia brought humanist warmth to digital reading, shaping how millions
            experienced text on screens during the internet's formative years.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-h3 font-semibold text-text-primary mb-4">Notable Works</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 pl-6 mb-8">
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Bell Centennial (1977)</strong> — Optimized for
              small sizes in phone directories
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Verdana (1996)</strong> — Screen-optimized humanist
              sans-serif for Microsoft
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Georgia (1996)</strong> — Screen-optimized humanist
              serif for digital reading
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Tahoma (1994)</strong> — Narrow humanist sans for
              tight spaces
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Charter (1987)</strong> — Economical typeface for
              low-resolution printers
            </li>
          </ul>

          <blockquote
            class="border-l-4 border-accent-primary bg-bg-secondary pl-8 pr-6 py-6 my-8 italic"
          >
            <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-primary">
              "Type is a beautiful group of letters, not a group of beautiful letters."
            </p>
          </blockquote>

          <h4 class="text-h3 font-semibold text-text-primary mb-4">Impact on Humanist Modernism</h4>
          <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
            Carter brought humanist modernism to the digital age. By optimizing typefaces for
            screens rather than imposing print aesthetics on digital media, he demonstrated that
            human-centered design means understanding context and constraints—then designing
            accordingly.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Oliver Reichenstein -->
      <article class="bg-bg-elevated border border-text-primary/10 rounded-sm overflow-hidden">
        <div class="bg-accent-primary/10 border-b border-accent-primary/20 p-8">
          <h2 class="text-h1 font-bold text-text-primary mb-2">Oliver Reichenstein</h2>
          <span class="text-body text-text-secondary block mb-1">Born 1978</span>
          <span
            class="inline-block bg-accent-primary text-white px-4 py-1 rounded-sm text-small font-medium"
            >Designer & Developer</span
          >
        </div>

        <div class="p-8">
          <h3 class="text-h2 font-semibold text-text-primary mb-6">
            Digital Content-First Pioneer
          </h3>

          <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary mb-6">
            Swiss designer Oliver Reichenstein founded iA (Information Architects) and created iA
            Writer, a writing app that became the gold standard for content-first digital design.
            Every aspect of iA Writer prioritizes the reading and writing experience—generous
            typography, minimal distractions, and thoughtful white space.
          </p>

          <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary mb-8">
            Reichenstein's work demonstrates how humanist modernism principles translate seamlessly
            to digital products when the focus remains on serving user needs.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-h3 font-semibold text-text-primary mb-4">Notable Works</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 pl-6 mb-8">
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">iA Writer</strong> — Distraction-free writing
              application
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">iA Duospace</strong> — Monospaced typeface family
              for code and writing
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">iA Writer Mono/Duo/Quattro</strong> — Custom
              typeface system for writing at different sizes
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">"Web Design is 95% Typography"</strong> —
              Influential article on digital design
            </li>
          </ul>

          <blockquote
            class="border-l-4 border-accent-primary bg-bg-secondary pl-8 pr-6 py-6 my-8 italic"
          >
            <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-primary">
              "Optimizing typography is optimizing readability, accessibility, usability(!), overall
              graphic balance."
            </p>
          </blockquote>

          <h4 class="text-h3 font-semibold text-text-primary mb-4">Impact on Humanist Modernism</h4>
          <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
            Reichenstein proved that humanist modernism isn't just a print tradition—it's the
            foundation of excellent digital design. His obsessive focus on typography, spacing, and
            content hierarchy influenced countless designers and products, helping establish
            human-centered design as digital best practice.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Richard Saul Wurman -->
      <article class="bg-bg-elevated border border-text-primary/10 rounded-sm overflow-hidden">
        <div class="bg-accent-primary/10 border-b border-accent-primary/20 p-8">
          <h2 class="text-h1 font-bold text-text-primary mb-2">Richard Saul Wurman</h2>
          <span class="text-body text-text-secondary block mb-1">Born 1935</span>
          <span
            class="inline-block bg-accent-primary text-white px-4 py-1 rounded-sm text-small font-medium"
            >Information Architect & Author</span
          >
        </div>

        <div class="p-8">
          <h3 class="text-h2 font-semibold text-text-primary mb-6">
            Founder of Information Architecture
          </h3>

          <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary mb-6">
            Architect, graphic designer, and author Richard Saul Wurman coined the term "information
            architecture" and founded the TED Conference. His work focuses on making complex
            information understandable—organizing content around how people actually think and learn
            rather than how databases are structured.
          </p>

          <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary mb-8">
            Wurman's emphasis on human understanding over systematic perfection embodies humanist
            modernism's core principle: serving cognitive needs first.
          </p>

          <h4 class="text-h3 font-semibold text-text-primary mb-4">Notable Works</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 pl-6 mb-8">
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Information Anxiety (1989)</strong> — Groundbreaking
              book on information overload
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Access Guide Series</strong> — City guidebooks
              organized by understanding, not alphabetically
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">TED Conference (founded 1984)</strong> — Ideas worth
              spreading, human-centered presentations
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Understanding USA</strong> — Data visualization
              projects making statistics comprehensible
            </li>
            <li class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Information Architects (1996)</strong> — Defining
              the discipline of IA
            </li>
          </ul>

          <blockquote
            class="border-l-4 border-accent-primary bg-bg-secondary pl-8 pr-6 py-6 my-8 italic"
          >
            <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-primary">
              "The most important thing is to understand the audience and to make the complex
              clear."
            </p>
          </blockquote>

          <h4 class="text-h3 font-semibold text-text-primary mb-4">Impact on Humanist Modernism</h4>
          <p class="text-body leading-comfortable text-text-secondary">
            Wurman established that good design isn't about imposing order—it's about creating
            understanding. His information architecture principles influenced web design, UX design,
            and content strategy, all centered on the humanist idea that structure should serve
            human cognition, not abstract logic.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
